## Observe the graph to understand the the motion
As you tweak the settings, observe the impact on the graph. You can mute or bypass the AnimateDiff, Frame Rate and Saving groups to render only the graph.

nodes.title: Note+ (mtb)
widgets_values:
## Type of frame distribution
Setting "linear" frame distribution makes the frames spaced out by the linear value. For example, if it's set to 16, the frames will be at positions 0, 16, 32, etc. To use the values in the box, set it to "dynamic".

nodes.title: Note+ (mtb)
widgets_values:
## Set duration of frame influence
1.0 equals around the distance between this and the next frames, 2.0 equals twice this. You can set these values for each frame individually in the field below.

nodes.title: Note+ (mtb)
widgets_values:
## Set prompts for each frame to improve adherence
Setting prompts to the right for each frame can increase adherence to the input images if the prompts match.

nodes.title: Note+ (mtb)
widgets_values:
## Understanding the settings
There are 3 main settings:
- Key frame position - Length of influence - Strength of influence
The type_of fields decide whether each of settings are the same for each frame or different.
When the type has been set to 'linear', you can adjust the value for every in with the _value fields.
When the type is set to 'dynamic', the text box below each setting are for the individual values - follow the format provided to set values for each frame.

nodes.title: Note+ (mtb)
widgets_values:
## Relative IPAdapter settings
IPAdapter settings are relative to the cn settings - they act like a multiplier on influence and strength. For example, a relative ipadapter influence of 1.3 will make the length of the ipadapter influence 1.3 times longer than the influence of the controlnet.

nodes.title: Note+ (mtb)
widgets_values:
## ControlNet strength
Set high and low point of influence strength. The number are the range the strength runs from and to - the first value is the low point, the last is the high.

nodes.title: Note+ (mtb)
widgets_values:
## Tweak motion_scale to change amount of movement
You can tweak motion_scale on the left to increase or decrease the amount of motion in the generation.

nodes.title: Note+ (mtb)
widgets_values:
# A Brief Guide
## Original Workflow Based on the workflow from https://github.com/banodoco/steerable-motion - the GitHub for the main custom node!
## What it does: This workflow will interpolate through the images you provide in order to create a fun animation :) Maybe tell a story, or just be creative!
## How to use this: 1. Select your images. You'll need at least two, but can easily add more.
2. Try the basic settings to start. Based on the resulting generation, try to understand what happened - you can learn about the settings and observe the graphs to the right. 3. Tweak the settings until you achieve your desired effect.
## What this will & won't be suitable for: I believe that this will be good for a wide range of storytelling-driven and abstract motion. However, it probably won't be good for complex motion - other approaches like vid2vid are far more suitable for this.
## If you're having problems I feel bad for you, son... but check the troubleshooting section [here](https://github.com/nerdyrodent/AVeryComfyNerd).

nodes.title: Note+ (mtb)
widgets_values:
## Batch size
Batch size should be the number of frames you want to generate + the interpolation buffer size (4 by default).
